[The newswires are filled with reports of suspected SARS cases in a number
of countries that do not show up on the WHO update information. One
possible explanation is that these are suspected cases and the WHO updates
are presenting probable cases (with the exception of the data released by
the USA which does include both suspected and probable cases). This
confusion and discrepancy in reported cases will most likely continue until
there is a definitive etiology, with reliable laboratory testing to allow
for confirmation of actual infection with the etiologic agent responsible
for producing the clinical picture currently referred to as SARS.
In addition, in today's newswires were multiple iterations of theories that
the etiologic agent is a virus that has jumped species from animals (as the
newswires have mentioned pigs, fowl and in one case owls). The verdict on
the etiology and the origin of the etiologic agent is not out yet, and we
have decided to refrain from posting these newswires pending solid
scientific information.
The WHO update for today highlights the additional reports in the past 24
hours. For those who have chosen to read this comment first:
"As of today, a cumulative total of 2270 SARS cases and 79 deaths have been
reported from 16 countries. This represents an increase of 47 cases and 1
death (in Hong Kong) compared with yesterday. New cases were reported in
Canada (4), Hong Kong (26), Taiwan, China (1), France (2), Singapore (3),
the United States of America (13), and Viet Nam (1). Brazil reported [its]
first probable case. 2 of Romania's 3 reported cases, one of the 2 cases in
the Republic of Ireland, and the single case in Spain were removed from the
list when determined to have other causes." - Mod.MPP]
